      "solution": "base = int(input())\nnumber = input()\ndef addition_base_k(a: str, b: str, k: int) -> str:\n    char_to_val = {c: i for i, c in enumerate(\"0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ\")}\n    val_to_char = \"0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ\"\n    i, j = len(a) - 1, len(b) - 1\n    carry = 0\n    result = []\n    while i >= 0 or j >= 0 or carry:\n        va = char_to_val[a[i]] if i >= 0 else 0\n        vb = char_to_val[b[j]] if j >= 0 else 0\n        total = va + vb + carry\n        result.append(val_to_char[total % k])\n        carry = total // k\n        i -= 1\n        j -= 1\n    return ''.join(reversed(result))\n\ndef isPalindromic(number:str)->bool:\n    return number == number[::-1]\n\n\ndef MirrorAddOpp(number:str)->str:\n    return addition_base_k(number, number[::-1],base)\n\n\niteration = 0\nwhile True:\n    number = MirrorAddOpp(number)\n    iteration += 1\n    if isPalindromic(number) or iteration > 1000:\n        break\n\nif (iteration > 1000):\n    print(\"Candidate Lychrel\")\nelse:\n    print(iteration)\n    print(number)",
      "statement": "<<Consider the following iterative process:>>\n\n<<1. >>Take a number written in a given base.\n<<2. >>Reverse its digits.\n<<3. >>Add the original number and the reversed number (in the same base).\nThis process is called the <<reverse-and-add process>>.\n\nBy repeatedly applying this process, most numbers eventually become palindromic (a number that reads the same forwards and backwards in the given base).\n\n<<Lychrel Numbers>>\n\nSome numbers do not produce a palindromic number after {{1000}} iterations. For this puzzle, these numbers will be called candidate Lychrel numbers.\n\nFurther reading about Lychrel numbers: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lychrel_number\n\n<<Task>>\n\nGiven a [[base]] and a [[number]], your task is to determine the first palindromic number obtained by applying the reverse-and-add process <<at least once>> (even if the original number is palindromic).\n\nExample in base 10 with the number 5678: \n5678 + 8765 = 14443\n14443 + 34441 = 48884 which is a palindromic number\nAnswer: 48884 in 2 iterations\n\nExample in base 16 with the number AE:\nAE + EA = 198\n198 + 891 = A29\nA29 + 92A = 1353\n1353 + 3531 = 4884 which is a palindromic number\nAnswer: 4884 in 4 iterations",
